00:14:11.480 --> 00:14:16.840
 - Okay, it is time for fact number two, and that is Andy.

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:22.400
 - My fact is, from 1990 to 2018, there was an award given out every year for the most

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:25.720
 human human.

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:26.720
 - You sounded so robotic.

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:28.400
 (laughter)

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:29.880
 - This was a prize that was given out.

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:31.680
 It was a subsection of a bigger prize, right?

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:34.360
 And it's all to do with the Turing test.

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:36.040
 So for anyone who hasn't heard of that before,

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:40.760
 that's the idea that Alan Turing, brilliant computer scientist,

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:44.280
 proposed in the '50s that the way you would be able to tell

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:48.040
 when we had artificial intelligence is if a human is conversing

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:51.840
 with someone who's unseen and they are unable to tell

00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:54.760
 whether they're talking to a person or a computer.

00:14:54.760 --> 00:14:57.040
 That's when we'll have true artificial intelligence.

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:59.080
 - Which I would say is now, right?

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:01.040
 - Oh yeah, people are falling in love with AI's left-right

00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:03.560
 and said, "We've way past the Turing test."

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:05.560
 So by that metric, we've done it.

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:07.760
 - So when we started this podcast, it wasn't true.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:09.360
 - Absolutely, absolutely.

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:11.600
 Yeah, so that's the idea of the Turing test.

00:15:11.600 --> 00:15:15.800
 And there was an annual prize during those years starting in 1990,

00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:19.480
 called the Lubner Prize, where people would bring along

00:15:19.480 --> 00:15:21.720
 their own chatbots, and they would be training them

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:23.080
 and improving them every year.

00:15:23.080 --> 00:15:26.160
 And if your chatbot managed to fool a human judge,

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:27.120
 you would win a prize.

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:30.400
 There would be several thousand dollars for the most human computer.

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:33.320
 But as part of that, you obviously had to have some humans

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:36.640
 being behind the screen, chatting back for the judges

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:39.480
 to have any sense of like, are you talking to a computer or a human?

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:41.720
 Sometimes you'd be talking to one, sometimes the other.

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:46.320
 And as a separate prize, the judges would pick the human chatter

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:50.280
 who was most convincingly human and give them a hundred dollars

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:51.760
 or some small prize.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:53.960
 - I think this is a problem with the experiment,

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:58.600
 because if the human is then changing their attitude

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:02.240
 and the way that they respond because they're trying to get a prize,

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:04.040
 then that changes the experiment, right?

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:05.200
 - And that is what happened, right?

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:08.040
 Brian Christian, who won the most human prize,

00:16:08.040 --> 00:16:09.240
 he wrote a whole book about it,

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:13.200
 and part of the book was telling how he prepared to be human

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:14.320
 as part of the test.

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:16.560
 And so he did study to be human, to win it.

00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:18.320
 - That feels like it's kind of cheating.

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:19.520
 Isn't the whole point of that?

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:20.960
 You've got to be yourself.

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:22.680
 - The rising to an exam is not cheating.

00:16:22.680 --> 00:16:24.760
 And if the exam is, are you a human?

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:26.120
 It's completely reasonable to prep.

00:16:26.120 --> 00:16:27.800
 - But we're testing the computers, right?

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:28.640
 - Yeah.

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:31.720
 - If the whole point of the exam is to test the marking system

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:35.440
 and you change your answers to make them completely wrong

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:37.400
 or completely right, then that's not a very good way

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:38.640
 of testing the marking system.

00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:40.800
 - I think he was just practicing being himself

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.960
 and being authentic in conversation

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:44.560
 and being truly human.

